Information Markets vs. Opinion Pools: 
content:
1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:In this paper, we examine the relative forecast accuracy of information markets versus expert aggregation .
1-2:We leverage a unique data source of almost 2000 people"s subjective probability judgments on 2003 US National Football League games and compare with the market probabilities given by two different information markets on exactly the same events .
1-3:We combine assessments of multiple experts via linear and logarithmic aggregation functions to form pooled predictions .
1-4:Prices in information markets are used to derive market predictions .
1-5:Our results show that, at the same time point ahead of the game, information markets provide as accurate predictions as pooled expert assessments .
1-6:In screening pooled expert predictions, we find that arithmetic average is a robust and efficient pooling function; weighting expert assessments according to their past performance does not improve accuracy of pooled predictions; and logarithmic aggregation functions offer bolder predictions than linear aggregation functions .
1-7:The results provide insights into the predictive performance of information markets, and the relative merits of selecting among various opinion pooling methods .
1-8:J.4 [Computer Applications]: Social and Behavioral .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:Forecasting is a ubiquitous endeavor in human societies .
2-2:For decades, scientists have been developing and exploring various forecasting methods, which can be roughly divided into statistical and non statistical approaches .
2-3:Statistical approaches require not only the existence of enough historical data but also that past data contains valuable information about the future event .
2-4:When these conditions can not be met, non statistical approaches that rely on judgmental information about the future event could be better choices .
2-5:One widely used non statistical method is to elicit opinions from experts .
2-6:Since experts are not generally in agreement, many belief aggregation methods have been proposed to combine expert opinions together and form a single prediction .
2-7:These belief aggregation methods are called opinion pools, which have been extensively studied in statistics [20, 24, 38], and management sciences [8, 9, 30, 31], and applied in many domains such as group decision making [29] and risk analysis [12] .
2-8:With the fast growth of the Internet, information markets have recently emerged as a promising non statistical forecasting tool .
2-9:Information markets (sometimes called prediction markets, idea markets, or event markets) are markets designed for aggregating information and making predictions about future events .
2-10:To form the predictions, information markets tie payoffs of securities to outcomes of events .
2-11:For example, in an information market to predict the result of a US professional National Football League game, say New England vs Carolina, the security pays a certain amount of money per share to its holders if and only if New England wins the game .
2-12:Otherwise, it pays off nothing .
2-13:The security price before the game reflects the consensus expectation of market traders about the probability of New England winning the game .
2-14:Such markets are becoming very popular .
2-15:The Iowa Electronic Markets [2] are real money futures markets to predict economic and political events such as elections .
2-16:The Hollywood Stock Exchange [3] is a virtual (play money) exchange for trading securities to forecast future box office proceeds of new movies, and the outcomes of entertainment awards, etc .
2-17:TradeSports.com [7], a real money betting exchange registered in Ireland, hosts markets for sports, political, entertainment, and financial events .
2-18:The Foresight Exchange [4] allows traders to wager play money on unresolved scientific questions or other claims of public interest, and NewsFutures.com"s World News Exchange [1] has 58 popular sports and financial betting markets, also grounded in a play money currency .
2-19:Despite the popularity of information markets, one of the most important questions to ask is: how accurately can information markets predict? Previous research in general shows that information markets are remarkably accurate .
2-20:The political election markets at IEM predict the election outcomes better than polls [16, 17, 18, 19] .
2-21:Prices in HSX and FX have been found to give as accurate or more accurate predictions than judgment of individual experts [33, 34, 37] .
2-22:However, information markets have not been calibrated against opinion pools, except for Servan Schreiber et .
2-23:al [36], in which the authors compare two information markets against arithmetic average of expert opinions .
2-24:Since information markets, in nature, offer an adaptive and selforganized mechanism to aggregate opinions of market participants, it is interesting to compare them with existing opinion pooling methods, to evaluate the performance of information markets from another perspective .
2-25:The comparison will provide beneficial guidance for practitioners to choose the most appropriate method for their needs .
2-26:This paper contributes to the literature in two ways: (1) As an initial attempt to compare information markets with opinion pools of multiple experts, it leads to a better understanding of information markets and their promise as an alternative institution for obtaining accurate forecasts; (2) In screening opinion pools to be used in the comparison, we cast insights into relative performances of different opinion pools .
2-27:In terms of prediction accuracy, we compare two information markets with several linear and logarithmic opinion pools (LinOP and LogOP) at predicting the results of NFL games .
2-28:Our results show that at the same time point ahead of the game, information markets provide as accurate predictions as our carefully selected opinion pools .
2-29:In selecting the opinion pools to be used in our comparison, we find that arithmetic average is a robust and efficient pooling function; weighting expert assessments according to their past performances does not improve the prediction accuracy of opinion pools; and LogOP offers bolder predictions than LinOP .
2-30:The remainder of the paper is organized as follows .
2-31:Section 2 reviews popular opinion pooling methods .
2-32:Section 3 introduces the basics of information markets .
2-33:Data sets and our analysis methods are described in Section 4 .
2-34:We present results and analysis in Section 5, followed by conclusions in Section 6. .
3 REVIEW OF OPINION POOLS :
3-1:Clemen and Winkler [12] classify opinion pooling methods into two broad categories: mathematical approaches and behavioral approaches .
3-2:In mathematical approaches, the opinions of individual experts are expressed as subjective probability distributions over outcomes of an uncertain event .
3-3:They are combined through various mathematical methods to form an aggregated probability distribution .
3-4:Genest and Zidek [24] and French [20] provide comprehensive reviews of mathematical approaches .
3-5:Mathematical approaches can be further distinguished into axiomatic approaches and Bayesian approaches .
3-6:Axiomatic approaches apply prespecified functions that map expert opinions, expressed as a set of individual probability distributions, to a single aggregated probability distribution .
3-7:These pooling functions are justified using axioms or certain desirable properties .
3-8:Two of the most common pooling functions are the linear opinion pool (LinOP) and the logarithmic opinion pool (LogOP) .
3-9:Using LinOP, the aggregate probability distribution is a weighted arithmetic mean of individual probability distributions: p(θ) = n i=1 wipi(θ), (1) where pi(θ) is expert i"s probability distribution of uncertain event θ, p(θ) represents the aggregate probability distribution, wi"s are weights for experts, which are usually nonnegative and sum to 1, and n is the number of experts .
3-10:Using LogOP, the aggregate probability distribution is a weighted geometric mean of individual probability distributions: p(θ) = k n i=1 pi(θ)wi , (2) where k is a normalization constant to ensure that the pooled opinion is a probability distribution .
3-11:Other axiomatic pooling methods often are extensions of LinOP [22], LogOP [23], or both [13] .
3-12:Winkler [39] and Morris [29, 30] establish the early framework of Bayesian aggregation methods .
3-13:Bayesian approaches assume as if there is a decision maker who has a prior probability distribution over event θ and a likelihood function over expert opinions given the event .
3-14:This decision maker takes expert opinions as evidence and updates its priors over the event and opinions according to Bayes rule .
3-15:The resulted posterior probability distribution of θ is the pooled opinion .
3-16:Behavioral approaches have been widely studied in the field of group decision making and organizational behavior .
3-17:The important assumption of behavioral approaches is that, through exchanging opinions or information, experts can eventually reach an equilibrium where further interaction won"t change their opinions .
3-18:One of the best known behavioral approaches is the Delphi technique [28] .
3-19:Typically, this method and its variants do not allow open discussion, but each expert has chance to judge opinions of other experts, and is given feedback .
3-20:Experts then can reassess their opinions and repeat the process until a consensus or a smaller spread of opinions is achieved .
3-21:Some other behavioral methods, such as the Nominal Group technique [14], promote open discussions in controlled environments .
3-22:Each approach has its pros and cons .
3-23:Axiomatic approaches are easy to use .
3-24:But they don"t have a normative basis to choose weights .
3-25:In addition, several impossibility results (e.g., Genest [21]) show that no aggregation function can satisfy all desired properties of an opinion pool, unless the pooled opinion degenerates to a single individual opinion, which effectively implies a dictator .
3-26:Bayesian approaches are nicely based on the normative Bayesian framework .
3-27:However, it is sometimes frustratingly difficult to apply because it requires either (1) constructing an obscenely complex joint prior over the event and opinions (often impractical even in terms of storage space complexity, not to mention from an elicitation standpoint) or (2) making strong assumptions about the prior, like conditional independence of experts .
3-28:Behavior approaches allow experts to dynamically improve their information and revise their opinions during interactions, but many of them are not fixed or completely specified, and can"t guarantee convergence or repeatability .
3-29:59 .
4 HOW INFORMATION MARKETS WORK :
4-1:Much of the enthusiasm for information markets stems from Hayek hypothesis [26] and efficient market hypothesis [15] .
4-2:Hayek, in his classic critique of central planning in 1940"s, claims that the price system in a competitive market is a very efficient mechanism to aggregate dispersed information among market participants .
4-3:The efficient market hypothesis further states that, in an efficient market, the price of a security almost instantly incorporates all available information .
4-4:The market price summarizes all relevant information across traders, hence is the market participants" consensus expectation about the future value of the security .
4-5:Empirical evidence supports both hypotheses to a large extent [25, 27, 35] .
4-6:Thus, when associating the value of a security with the outcome of an uncertain future event, market price, by revealing the consensus expectation of the security value, can indirectly predict the outcome of the event .
4-7:This idea gives rise to information markets .
4-8:For example, if we want to predict which team will win the NFL game between New England and Carolina, an information market can trade a security $100 if New England defeats Carolina, whose payoff per share at the end of the game is specified as follow: $100 if New England wins the game; $0 otherwise .
4-9:The security price should roughly equal the expected payoff of the security in an efficient market .
4-10:The time value of money usually can be ignored because durations of most information markets are short .
4-11:Assuming exposure to risk is roughly equal for both outcomes, or that there are sufficient effectively risk neutral speculators in the market, the price should not be biased by the risk attitudes of various players in the market .
4-12:Thus, p = Pr(Patriots win) × 100 + [1 − Pr(Patriots win)] × 0, where p is the price of the security $100 if New England defeats Carolina and Pr(Patriots win) is the probability that New England will win the game .
4-13:Observing the security price p before the game, we can derive Pr(Patriots win), which is the market participants" collective prediction about how likely it is that New England will win the game .
4-14:The above security is a winner takes all contract .
4-15:It is used when the event to be predicted is a discrete random variable with disjoint outcomes (in this case binary) .
4-16:Its price predicts the probability that a specific outcome will be realized .
4-17:When the outcome of a prediction problem can be any value in a continuous interval, we can design a security that pays its holder proportional to the realized value .
4-18:This kind of security is what Wolfers and Zitzewitz [40] called an index contract .
4-19:It predicts the expected value of a future outcome .
4-20:Many other aspects of a future event such as median value of outcome can also be predicted in information markets by designing and trading different securities .
4-21:Wolfers and Zitzewitz [40] provide a summary of the main types of securities traded in information markets and what statistical properties they can predict .
4-22:In practice, conceiving a security for a prediction problem is only one of the many decisions in designing an effective information market .
4-23:Spann and Skiera [37] propose an initial framework for designing information markets. .
5 DESIGN OF ANALYSIS :
5-1:4.1 Data Sets Our data sets cover 210 NFL games held between September 28th, 2003 and December 28th, 2003 .
5-2:NFL games are very suitable for our purposes because: (1) two online exchanges and one online prediction contest already exist that provide data on both information markets and the opinions of self identified experts for the same set of games; (2) the popularity of NFL games in the United States provides natural incentives for people to participate in information markets and or the contest, which increases liquidity of information markets and improves the quality and number of opinions in the contest; (3) intense media coverage and analysis of the profiles and strengths of teams and individual players provide the public with much information so that participants of information markets and the contest can be viewed as knowledgeable regarding to the forecasting goal .
5-3:Information market data was acquired, by using a specially designed crawler program, from TradeSports.com"s Football NFL markets [7] and NewsFutures.com"s Sports Exchange [1] .
5-4:For each NFL game, both TradeSports and NewsFutures have a winner takes all information market to predict the game outcome .
5-5:We introduce the design of the two markets according to Spann and Skiera"s three steps for designing an information market [37] as below .
5-6:• Choice of forecasting goal: Markets at both TradeSports and NewsFutures aim at predicting which one of the two teams will win a NFL football game .
5-7:They trade similar winner takes all securities that pay off 100 if a team wins the game and 0 if it loses the game .
5-8:Small differences exist in how they deal with ties .
5-9:In the case of a tie, TradeSports will unwind all trades that occurred and refund all exchange fees, but the security is worth 50 in NewsFutures .
5-10:Since the probability of a tie is usually very low (much less the 1%), prices at both markets effectively represent the market participants" consensus assessment of the probability that the team will win .
5-11:• Incentive for participation and information revelation: TradeSports and NewsFutures use different incentives for participation and information revelation .
5-12:TradeSports is a real money exchange .
5-13:A trader needs to open and fund an account with a minimum of $100 to participate in the market .
5-14:Both profits and losses can occur as a result of trading activity .
5-15:On the contrary, a trader can register at NewsFutures for free and get 2000 units of Sport Exchange virtual money at the time of registration .
5-16:Traders at NewsFutures will not incur any real financial loss .
5-17:They can accumulate virtual money by trading securities .
5-18:The virtual money can then be used to bid for a few real prizes at NewsFutures" online shop .
5-19:• Financial market design: Both markets at TradeSports and NewsFutures use the continuous double auction as their trading mechanism .
5-20:TradeSports charges a small fee on each security transaction and expiry, while NewsFutures does not .
5-21:We can see that the main difference between two information markets is real money vs .
5-22:virtual money .
5-23:Servan Schreiber 60 et .
5-24:al [36] have compared the effect of money on the performance of the two information markets and concluded that the prediction accuracy of the two markets are at about the same level .
5-25:Not intending to compare these two markets, we still use both markets in our analysis to ensure that our findings are not accidental .
5-26:We obtain the opinions of 1966 self identified experts for NFL games from the ProbabilityFootball online contest [5], one of several ProbabilitySports contests [6] .
5-27:The contest is free to enter .
5-28:Participants of the contest are asked to enter their subjective probability that a team will win a game by noon on the day of the game .
5-29:Importantly, the contest evaluates the participants" performance via the quadratic scoring rule: s = 100 − 400 × Prob Lose2 , (3) where s represents the score that a participant earns for the game, and Prob Lose is the probability that the participant assigns to the actual losing team .
5-30:The quadratic score is one of a family of so called proper scoring rules that have the property that an expert"s expected score is maximized when the expert reports probabilities truthfully .
5-31:For example, for a game team A vs .
5-32:team B, if a player assigns 0.5 to both team A and B, his her score for the game is 0 no matter which team wins .
5-33:If he she assigns 0.8 to team A and 0.2 to team B, showing that he is confident in team A"s winning, he she will score 84 points for the game if team A wins, and lose 156 points if team B wins .
5-34:This quadratic scoring rule rewards bold predictions that are right, but penalizes bold predictions that turn out to be wrong .
5-35:The top players, measured by accumulated scores over all games, win the prizes of the contest .
5-36:The suggested strategy at the contest website is to make picks for each game that match, as closely as possible, the probabilities that each team will win .
5-37:This strategy is correct if the participant seeks to maximize expected score .
5-38:However, as prizes are awarded only to the top few winners, participants" goals are to maximize the probability of winning, not maximize expected score, resulting in a slightly different and more risk seeking optimization.1 Still, as far as we are aware, this data offer the closest thing available to true subjective probability judgments from so many people over so many public events that have corresponding information markets .
5-39:4.2 Methods of Analysis In order to compare the prediction accuracy of information markets and that of opinion pools, we proceed to derive predictions from market data of TradeSports and NewsFutures, form pooled opinions using expert data from ProbabilityFootball contest, and specify the performance measures to be used .
5-40:4.2.1 Deriving Predictions For information markets, deriving predictions is straightforward .
5-41:We can take the security price and divide it by 100 to get the market"s prediction of the probability that a team will win .
5-42:To match the time when participants at the ProbabilityFootball contest are required to report their probability assessments, we derive predictions using the last trade price before noon on the day of the game .
5-43:For more 1 Ideally, prizes would be awarded by lottery in proportion to accumulated score .
5-44:than half of the games, this time is only about an hour earlier than the game starting time, while it is several hours earlier for other games .
5-45:Two sets of market predictions are derived: • NF: Prediction equals NewsFutures" last trade price before noon of the game day divided by 100 .
5-46:• TS: Prediction equals TradeSports" last trade price before noon of the game day divided by 100 .
5-47:We apply LinOP and LogOP to ProbabilityFootball data to obtain aggregate expert predictions .
5-48:The reason that we do not consider other aggregation methods include: (1) data from ProbabilityFootball is only suitable for mathematical pooling methods we can rule out behavioral approaches, (2) Bayesian aggregation requires us to make assumptions about the prior probability distribution of game outcomes and the likelihood function of expert opinions: given the large number of games and participants, making reasonable assumptions is difficult, and (3) for axiomatic approaches, previous research has shown that simpler aggregation methods often perform better than more complex methods [12] .
5-49:Because the output of LogOP is indeterminate if there are probability assessments of both 0 and 1 (and because assessments of 0 and 1 are dictatorial using LogOP), we add a small number 0.01 to an expert opinion if it is 0, and subtract 0.01 from it if it is 1 .
5-50:In pooling opinions, we consider two influencing factors: weights of experts and number of expert opinions to be pooled .
5-51:For weights of experts, we experiment with equal weights and performance based weights .
5-52:The performancebased weights are determined according to previous accumulated score in the contest .
5-53:The score for each game is calculated according to equation 3, the scoring rule used in the ProbabilityFootball contest .
5-54:For the first week, since no previous scores are available, we choose equal weights .
5-55:For later weeks, we calculate accumulated past scores for each player .
5-56:Because the cumulative scores can be negative, we shift everyone"s score if needed to ensure the weights are non negative .
5-57:Thus, wi = cumulative scorei + shift n j=1(cumulative scorej + shift) .
5-58:(4) where shift equals 0 if the smallest cumulative scorej is non negative, and equals the absolute value of the smallest cumulative scorej otherwise .
5-59:For simplicity, we call performance weighted opinion pool as weighted, and equally weighted opinion pool as unweighted .
5-60:We will use them interchangeably in the remaining of the paper .
5-61:As for the number of opinions used in an opinion pool, we form different opinion pools with different number of experts .
5-62:Only the best performing experts are selected .
5-63:For example, to form an opinion pool with 20 expert opinions, we choose the top 20 participants .
5-64:Since there is no performance record for the first week, we use opinions of all participants in the first week .
5-65:For week 2, we select opinions of 20 individuals whose scores in the first week are among the top 20 .
5-66:For week 3, 20 individuals whose cumulative scores of week 1 and 2 are among the top 20s are selected .
5-67:Experts are chosen in a similar way for later weeks .
5-68:Thus, the top 20 participants can change from week to week .
