8-48:We then take a closer look at prediction accuracy of information markets and opinion pools using the three performance measures .
8-49:Table 3 displays mean values of these measures over 210 games .
8-50:Numbers in parentheses are standard errors, which estimate the standard deviation of the mean .
8-51:To take into consideration of skewness of distributions, we also report median values of accuracy measures in Table 4 .
8-52:Judged by the mean values of accuracy measures in Table 3, all methods have similar accuracy levels, with NF and TS slightly better than the opinion pools .
8-53:However, the median values of accuracy measures indicate that LogAll u and Log All w opinion pools are more accurate than all other predictions .
8-54:We employ the randomization test [32] to study whether the differences in prediction accuracy presented in Table 3 and Table 4 are statistically significant .
8-55:The basic idea of randomization test is that, by randomly swapping predictions of two methods numerous times, an empirical distribution for the difference of prediction accuracy can be constructed .
8-56:Using this empirical distribution, we are then able to evaluate that at what confidence level the observed difference reflects a real difference .
8-57:For example, the mean absolute error of NF is higher than that of Log All u by 0.0229, as shown in Table 3 .
8-58:To test whether this difference is statistically significant, we shuﬄe predictions from two methods, randomly label half of predictions as NF and the other half as Log All u, and compute the difference of mean absolute error of the newly formed NF and Log All u data .
8-59:The above procedure is repeated 10,000 times .
8-60:The 10,000 differences of mean absolute error results in an empirical distribution of the difference .
8-61:Comparing our observed difference, 0.0229, with this distribution, we find that the observed difference is greater than 75.37% of the empirical differences .
8-62:This leads us to conclude that the difference of mean absolute error between NF and Log All u is not statistically significant, if we choose the level of significance to be 0.05 .
8-63:Table 5 and Table 6 are results of randomization test for mean and median differences respectively .
